This Week's Demos (May 11, 2026)VMaaS

Dedicated VM cluster (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hXveDei6GiTlmMPUjt54ID_67FBu4tpK/view>
13:34 - 25:50)

   -

   Dedicated cluster mode separates the OSAC/control-plane deployment from
   the VM workload cluster, allowing each to be managed and scaled
   independently.
   -

   Full VM lifecycle management is supported.
   -

   Console proxy is available for VM serial console access.
   -

   Follow-up Actions
   -

      Add VNC support for graphical VM console access.

Windows VM (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hXveDei6GiTlmMPUjt54ID_67FBu4tpK/view>
36:45 - 51:22)

   -

   Windows VM support requires a different flow because there is no
   official Windows container disk image.
   -

   Instead of booting from a container disk, OSAC should support creating
   VMs from an existing golden image/data volume.
   -

   Windows also requires specific initialization handling, including
   hostname limitations and Sysprep configuration.
   -

   The current flow takes too long for regular usage, with boot time around
   15 minutes, so we need a more efficient provisioning path.
   -

   Follow-up Actions


   -

   Consider adding a guest operating system flag to the fulfillment CLI and
   ComputeInstance API.
   -

   Support creating/starting VMs directly from existing data volumes.

Storage tenant on boarding (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1FUSrN5Deg3iCKH8FfdADj6-p__64lVrD/view>
13:34 - 25:50)

   -

   Automated storage class creation when OSAC tenant is created, labeled
   with tenant name.
   -

   Tenant controller triggers Ansible AAP job to provision storage classes.
   -

   Self-healing: recreates storage class if accidentally deleted.
   -

   Deprovisioning: removes storage classes when a tenant is deleted.
   -

   Follow-up Actions
   -

      Define a high-level storage integration model for different vendors
      and services.
      -

      Support multiple storage tiers (fast, standard) per tenant.
      -

      Personalize each cloned StorageClass with tenant-specific
      configuration, such as credentials, storage pool/slot etc.

Cross-Cutting Capabilities

Move to keycloak organizations (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hXveDei6GiTlmMPUjt54ID_67FBu4tpK/view>
3:02 - 13:03)

   -

   Today, using a separate Keycloak realm per tenant creates repeated setup
   and operational overhead.
   -

   Moving to Keycloak organizations allows each OSAC tenant to map to a
   Keycloak organization instead of a separate realm.
   -

   This reduces duplication and improves scalability by sharing common
   clients, roles, and IDP configuration across tenants.
   -

   OSAC will use predefined roles, such as tenant-admin and
   tenant-idp-manager, instead of redefining them per tenant.
   -

   The implementation includes CRUD support for Keycloak organizations,
   with proper sync and cleanup of break-glass accounts and users.
   -

   Follow-up Actions


   -

   Implement tenant admin APIs for role management, identity provider
   management, and project management.
   -

   Add external IDP integration, where tenant admins configure service
   account/client credentials in their IDP, and OSAC handles the organization
   login redirection flow.

Vast Integration (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1llqB8-PQaiLJ5RMEh_o_5asP3TWK48xP/view?usp=drive_link>
)

   -

   OSAC now supports a Vast storage integration that automates StorageClass
   provisioning.
   -

   When a tenant is onboarded, the system creates the required backend
   storage resources and tenant-specific StorageClasses.
   -

   Storage tiers can be updated dynamically, for example by adding a
   high-IOPS tier.
   -

   When a new tier is added, OSAC automatically creates the matching Vast
   backend resources, such as QoS policies and views.
   -

   This demonstrates the current backend-specific storage flow, while
   highlighting the need for a more generic storage model.
   -

   Follow-up Actions


   -

   Define a generic storage API that can support multiple storage vendors
   and services.
   -

   Formalize the storage integration design, including how backend-specific
   configuration should map into OSAC APIs.

Local Dev environment Overview (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1FUSrN5Deg3iCKH8FfdADj6-p__64lVrD/view>
36:08 - 49:40)

   -

   OSAC installation is currently long, manual, and error-prone, which
   slows down both developers and CI.
   -

   Cluster tool improves this by starting SNO clusters from pre-built
   snapshots instead of running the full 30–45 minute installation flow.
   -

   This allows developers to get from zero to a working OSAC cluster in
   about 20 minutes.
   -

   The tool refreshes the cloned cluster by updating hostnames,
   certificates, and application-level resources so the snapshot can be reused
   safely.
   -

   CI now uses cluster tool with pre-built OSAC snapshots from Quay,
   reducing the number of presubmit jobs and shortening total test time from
   around 2.5 hours to about 1 hour.
   -

   Current challenges include large snapshot size, around 50 GB, and
   keeping snapshots fresh when third-party dependencies change.
   -

   Follow-up Actions


   -

   Add nightly snapshot rebuilds to keep snapshots fresh.
   -

   Extend cluster tool support for Cluster as a Service flows.
   -

   Explore booting agents after the SNO cluster is running.

UI

Fulfillment service integration with the UI on the tenant flow (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hXveDei6GiTlmMPUjt54ID_67FBu4tpK/view>
51:30 - 58:40)

   -

   The UI is moving from mocked flows toward integration with real data
   from the fulfillment service.
   -

   The current VMaaS flow supports creating VMs from templates, customizing
   VM properties such as vCPU count and disk size, and performing lifecycle
   actions like start, stop, and delete.
   -

   Follow-up Actions


   -

   Add Cluster as a Service support to the UI.
   -

   Complete the full authentication flow.
   -

   Replace templates with catalog items, giving users clearer
   provider-defined provisioning options.

------------------------------

Upcoming Demos:

   -

   OSAC Installer - Move to Helm based installer
   -

   Public IP attachment management - Extend the Public IP API so it can be
   used across OSAC services, including VMaaS, CaaS, BMaaS, and future
   consumers, instead of being limited to VM use cases.
   -

   Netris integration with OSAC Networking API - Update the existing Netris
   integration to use the standard OSAC Networking API, aligning it with the
   common networking flow.
   -

   Admin APIs - Add administrative APIs for role management, identity
   provider management, and project management.
   -

   External IDP support - API to add external IDPs.
   -

   Catalog Items - adds a user-facing layer above Ansible templates,
   allowing providers to expose multiple curated provisioning options that can
   reuse the same underlying Ansible role.
   -

   DPU network class - Add support for tenant network isolation using
   DPU/HBN-based networking.
   -

   Integration with BCM - Integrate with BCM as a server inventory backend.
   -

   BMaaS Profiles - package reusable bare-metal provisioning workflows,
   allowing OSAC to request hosts by profile instead of hard-coding
   backend-specific setup and cleanup steps.


